dict.string: Originating in the shoulder area, the bicep can be found on the front part of the upper arm and are attached to the radius and ulna (forearm bones) by tough connective tissues called tendons. When the bicep contracts, the tendon is pulled towards to head of the bicep, thus bending the elbow. As a consequence of this, the bicep is often referred to as a 'flexor', with it's partner being the tricep which acts as an 'extensor'. Traditionally, the size and solidity of the contracted bicep is a measure of traditional strength in lifting.
